[1] Iraq
[A] Duhok
Date: Wed 8 Jun 2022
Source: NRT [edited]
https://www.nrttv.com/EN/detail6/3653


The 2nd case of haemorrhagic fever has been recorded in Duhok province, bringing up the total number of cases in the Kurdistan Region to 4.

Akre Health Directorate announced on Wednesday [8 Jun 2022] that a 24-year-old woman from a village in Akre district has tested positive for haemorrhagic fever.

The directorate said that the woman was sent to Baghdad for medical tests and would stay there for treatment.

Special tests for the diagnosis of haemorrhagic fever are currently unavailable in the Kurdistan Region.

The directorate said the patient had contact with animals.

Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever is a viral disease usually transmitted by ticks, according to the WHO.

It can also be contracted through contact with animal tissues where the virus enters the bloodstream during and immediately post-slaughter of animals.

10 to 40% of those who contract the virus die as a result.

The Kurdistan Regional Government (KRG) Minister of Health, Saman Barzinji, said on 19 May 2022 that there had been 2 recorded haemorrhagic fever cases in the Kurdistan Region, both contracted from animals that were slaughtered in unlicensed locations.

He explained Congo fever was not a new disease and steps must be taken to prevent its spread.

