[B] Erbil
Date: Sat 11 Jun 2022
Source: Rudaw [edited]
https://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/110620222


The Kurdistan Region's health ministry spokesperson confirmed the 1st case of a death related to Congo fever on Saturday [11 Jun 2022]; the same day he told Rudaw that a COVID-19 patient died as a result of the respiratory disease after over 40 days of no recorded coronavirus fatalities.

The 1st case of the Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever was recorded in the Kurdistan Region on [10 May 2022]. The infected person was a 17-year-old from Erbil province. The Region has confirmed 4 cases of the fever so far, according to health ministry spokesperson Aso Hawezi.

Hawezi said in a statement released on the ministry's Facebook page on Saturday [11 Jun 2022] that one of these cases, a 27-year-old man from Erbil province's Khalifan subdistrict died earlier that day [11 Jun 2022]. The official did not identify the deceased.

The fever is tick-borne and causes severe hemorrhaging, according to the World Health Organization (WHO). It has been endemic to Iraq since 1979 and reappeared again last year [2021].

People are often infected after they are exposed to the blood of infected animals, for example after slaughtering livestock.

The Kurdistan Region had not recorded any coronavirus related deaths since [29 Apr 2022]. However, the spokesperson told Rudaw's Rawchi Hassan that a COVID-19 patient died on Saturday [11 Jun 2022].

The health ministry recorded 47 new cases of coronavirus on Friday [10 Jun 2022], bringing the total number of known cases to 438 477. Of this, 7450 have died.

